<doc id="29313" wikidata="Q7442989" url="?curid=29313" title="Second-system effect">
<text>The second-system effect or second-system syndrome is the tendency of small, elegant, and successful systems to be succeeded by over-engineered, bloated systems, due to inflated expectations and overconfidence.

The phrase was first used by Fred Brooks in his book &quot;The Mythical Man-Month&quot;, first published in 1975. It described the jump from a set of simple operating systems on the IBM 700/7000 series to OS/360 on the 360 series, which happened in 1964.

